by The Saucer Pilots » Thu Apr 08, 2021 12:48 pm

Polish Prussian Commonwealth wrote:
honestly I always hated HUMINT type people. I want to see more SIGINT and recon people and I want their actions to result in doorkicking, not casinos.


In my case, it's because I genuinely wouldn't mind the POV of pilots assigned to a pressurized tin can snapping photos.

Ever since I read about the Gary Powers incident in an encyclopedia when I was a kid, I was kinda fascinated with the theme of a cat-and-mouse game upheld by average joes who doing their best at a job. The 1st Cold War has that going on with the stakes at hand, it's still the era of B-50s and RB-47s making risky flights and going up against MiGs and SAMs. A self plug, but I guess it's why I'm so enthralled with my Nova character right now. I really wish I had more expertise in describing technical processes and operations to describe their role as pilot as half-decently as I tried to write about them as a captive.

BUT from experience and commentary in F7, techno-thrillers written by worldbuilders are a hit-or-miss as readers either take them as boring inventories or those interested in military fiction get excited by the hardware. TBH, I try my best to generically describe things as "bombers" or "fighters" or "reconnaissance craft" before making specifications that might turn casual readers away.

Cliche: having an immortal leader/character and not doing anything with them.

By that, I mean simply using it as a propaganda vessel, or by having them be some pampered aristocrat. For example, let's say your character is about 400-600 years of age, and you write them as being gleeful, having not experienced any form of hardship or loss. What makes them interesting, or even relatable to the reader? Pretty much nothing.

I'm guilty of this too, and it shows in some of my writing.

Another cliche in general.
Expecting special ops guys or more generally people deployed to warzones to not have high fatality rates and somehow are supersoldiers.

Why they are special is due to all the high risk. Things go bad and entire units kia due to stupid stuff like helicopter crashes. People's legs getting blown off, etc.
Remember the video of the boko haram fighter dumping a mag into the seal, that stuff happens. That 2001 Seal on Kandalhar is a exception to rule and they still had to exfil because engaging people tend to lead to death. Or that bomb that took out a bunch of Wagner operatives in Syria. Being obliterated by superior forces once position is compromised is a real and present danger and that's why they are almost always supported by a large contingent of QRF and CAS. That is if your not part of insurgent force. In those cases think of Dvar during operation Russelsprung, situation just as dure and requiring breaking contact from superior force and leaving with heavy losses. Not glamorous at all. Only appeal is the underdog aspect.
